Rating: 0
This recipe feeds so many that a half batch would be sufficient for my purposes. With the many parts required for the whole, the intent was to cook a full batch of sauces, reserving half in the freezer for next time. Assembling the casserole with only 1 pound of pasta required all of the sauce to entirely coat each layer. With 2 lbs of pasta, the dish would come out quite dry. Very generously salting the pasta water avoided any lack of salt that was noted by others. The bread crumb layer was deep and sandy and overwhelmed the small amount of cheese mixed into it. Reducing the crumbs to 1/4 to 1/2 cup would yield a topping more in balance with the casserole. The cinnamon and allspice came through with a lot of punch, reminiscent of Cincinatti Chili. With the sauce diluted over 2 lbs of pasta, this might be the right amount of seasoning but with the reduced pasta, that punch was nearly a knock-out. A generous 1/2 teaspoon of cinnamon and allspice would still allow these flavoura to be noticeable without overwhelming the dish. The pasta that began al dente became soft and flabby after being baked with all of the sauce. Better to leave it firmer than al dente and if necessary, mix a bit of the pasta water in with the meat sauce. This could be a convenient dish to make ahead when cooking for a crowd but is definitely too time-consuming and complex for a weeknight family supper.

Rating: 3
I am married to a Greek family (yes, you marry the ENTIRE family). The best way to add the missing salt in this recipe is with light-handed layers. Salt the pasta water. Salt the lamb mixture (1 tsp Kosher salt to start) before you simmer for 40 min. About 10 min. before it's done, remove a tablespoon of lamb mixture, let it cool and then taste it to see if it needs more, but remember there will be salt in every layer. Add a pinch of salt to the bechamel if you use Parmesan, but not if you use kefalotyri because the Greek cheese is much saltier than the Italian cheese. Nothing will taste worse than having to salt this dish at the table.

