Rating: 4
I halved the recipe and baked it in a 13x9 dish. This quantity serves 8 because it is so rich. I used parmesan instead of kefalotyri, although it is readily available here. (To the cook from Chicago: you can sell cheese made from unpasteurized milk as long as it has been aged). I would cut back on the nutmeg in the bechamel sauce next time and add a little more salt to the meat sauce. This is a great, make-ahead party dish.

Rating: 4
I made this last night for a gathering of 8 and thought it was very tasty, as did all my guests. But here are some suggestions (and problems). First, the meat sauce could use more garlic and needs LOTS of salt. It was amazing how different (and tasty) the sauce was once salt was added. Second, I don't know where the people at Gourmet found kefolyteri cheese, but good luck to anyone trying to find it. It's an unpasteurized cheese, and therefore illegal for most stores to sell. I live in Chicago where there are plenty of cheese shops and grocers with great cheese counters. None had this cheese, and a few had never even heard of it. Parmesan is fine. Third, they say this recipe serves 12-16. I had 8 guests who all had seconds, I took some to our upstairs neighbors and STILL had a third left over. This can easily feed 20. Which brings me to: Fourth, finding a pan big enough to hold all this was not easy. I ended up using a roasting pan because it was the only thing that could hold 2 pounds of pasta and a half-gallon of sauce. Unless you're used to cooking for large groups and have pans big enough, I'd recommend halving the recipe. All that said, it really is worth making. I made the meat sauce a day ahead, which not only enhanced the flavor, but made the whole process much easier and less time-consuming. The meat sauce is tasty (though I'm not a big fan of clove, others like it). And the béchamel sauce was divine! Perfect comfort food for a cold winter night.

